s of that beleaguered continent. Spokesmen of the Slave South drew up ambitious plans to seize the Amazon and develop this region by deporting the enslaved African-Americans there to toil. When the South seceded from the Union, it received significant support from Brazil, which correctly assumed that a Confederate defeat would be a mortal blow to slavery south of the border. After the Civil War, many Confederates, with slaves in tow, sought refuge as well as the survival of their peculiar institution in Brazil.Based on extensive research from archives on five continents, Gerald Horne breaks startling new ground in the history of slavery, uncovering its global dimensions and the degrees to which its defenders went to maintain it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSlave tradezAmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzBrazilxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aBased.  aGerald.  aHorne.  aarchives.  abreaks.  acontinents.  adefenders.  adegrees.  adimensions.  aextensive.  afive.  afrom.  aglobal.  aground.  ahistory.  amaintain.  aresearch.  aslavery.  astartling.  auncovering.  awent.  awhich.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814737286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814737286/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK